WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.386 align:middle line:90%


00:00:09.386 --> 00:00:14.820 align:middle line:90%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:14.820 --> 00:00:21.545 align:middle line:90%


00:00:21.545 --> 00:00:23.670 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA GARR: Are you going
through a breakdown that

00:00:23.670 --> 00:00:26.490 align:middle line:90%
seems to be lasting forever?

00:00:26.490 --> 00:00:29.040 align:middle line:84%
Are you being run by
unconscious behaviors

00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:34.014 align:middle line:84%
that prevent you from believing
you deserve a miracle?

00:00:34.014 --> 00:00:37.560 align:middle line:84%
Well, what if I told you there
is such a thing as a miracle

00:00:37.560 --> 00:00:41.010 align:middle line:84%
mentor, someone who has
figured out a formula for how

00:00:41.010 --> 00:00:43.620 align:middle line:84%
to create the
conditions for miracles

00:00:43.620 --> 00:00:47.440 align:middle line:90%
to naturally occur in your life?

00:00:47.440 --> 00:00:49.310 align:middle line:10%
Hi, I'm Lisa Garr,
and joining me,

00:00:49.310 --> 00:00:52.360 align:middle line:10%
is the number one New York
Times best-selling author

00:00:52.360 --> 00:00:55.440 align:middle line:10%
of, "Happy for No
Reason," Marci Shimoff.

00:00:55.440 --> 00:00:58.488 align:middle line:10%
Marcy is also the
co-author of six books

00:00:58.488 --> 00:01:00.280 align:middle line:10%
and the "Chicken Soup
for the Soul" series,

00:01:00.280 --> 00:01:03.700 align:middle line:10%
as well as a featured
teacher in "The Secret."

00:01:03.700 --> 00:01:06.880 align:middle line:84%
Currently, Marcy co-leads
a global online program

00:01:06.880 --> 00:01:10.840 align:middle line:84%
called "Your Year of Miracles"
that I'm also joining her on,

00:01:10.840 --> 00:01:14.080 align:middle line:84%
which helps thousands of
women from 42 countries

00:01:14.080 --> 00:01:16.510 align:middle line:90%
live more miraculous lives.

00:01:16.510 --> 00:01:19.460 align:middle line:84%
So clearly, she knows how to
create a miracle in her life.

00:01:19.460 --> 00:01:20.260 align:middle line:90%
Welcome.

00:01:20.260 --> 00:01:21.230 align:middle line:90%
I'm so glad you're here.

00:01:21.230 --> 00:01:22.750 align:middle line:84%
>>MARCI SHIMOFF: I'm so
happy, for great reason,

00:01:22.750 --> 00:01:23.930 align:middle line:84%
to get to be here
with you, Lisa.

00:01:23.930 --> 00:01:24.850 align:middle line:90%
This is so much fun.

00:01:24.850 --> 00:01:26.290 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Lots of good reasons.

00:01:26.290 --> 00:01:28.240 align:middle line:84%
But it wasn't always
like that for you, right?

00:01:28.240 --> 00:01:30.380 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: No, I was
not a happy camper.

00:01:30.380 --> 00:01:32.440 align:middle line:90%
I, actually, was born depressed.

00:01:32.440 --> 00:01:34.260 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: How is that possible?

00:01:34.260 --> 00:01:37.630 align:middle line:10%
>>SHIMOFF: I had a great family,
but I came out of the womb

00:01:37.630 --> 00:01:40.420 align:middle line:10%
with existential angst.

00:01:40.420 --> 00:01:42.690 align:middle line:84%
The kids were all playing,
I was about four or five,

00:01:42.690 --> 00:01:44.440 align:middle line:84%
and everybody's playing
in the playground,

00:01:44.440 --> 00:01:46.870 align:middle line:84%
and I just felt this
dark cloud around me.

00:01:46.870 --> 00:01:51.170 align:middle line:84%
And there was no explanation
for it at the time.

00:01:51.170 --> 00:01:53.975 align:middle line:84%
And when I was older,
I still felt depressed,

00:01:53.975 --> 00:01:54.850 align:middle line:90%
but I was very lucky.

00:01:54.850 --> 00:01:57.670 align:middle line:84%
And I was lucky because
I had a father who

00:01:57.670 --> 00:01:59.830 align:middle line:84%
was the happiest
person on the planet.

00:01:59.830 --> 00:02:01.780 align:middle line:10%
I call him my happiness mentor.

00:02:01.780 --> 00:02:04.690 align:middle line:10%
And he lived till he was 91.

00:02:04.690 --> 00:02:07.600 align:middle line:10%
And every morning he woke up,
he had a big smile on his face,

00:02:07.600 --> 00:02:09.729 align:middle line:10%
and his motto was, every
day that I'm breathing

00:02:09.729 --> 00:02:10.990 align:middle line:10%
is a good day.

00:02:10.990 --> 00:02:13.630 align:middle line:84%
And I remember, Lisa, one day
we were driving down the road

00:02:13.630 --> 00:02:15.850 align:middle line:84%
together, and I looked
at him, and I said,

00:02:15.850 --> 00:02:18.310 align:middle line:84%
Dad, what's your
best advice for life?

00:02:18.310 --> 00:02:21.410 align:middle line:84%
And he looked at me and he
said, honey, just be happy!

00:02:21.410 --> 00:02:22.183 align:middle line:90%


00:02:22.183 --> 00:02:24.350 align:middle line:84%
And I threw my arms up into
the air in frustration--

00:02:24.350 --> 00:02:24.910 align:middle line:90%
I was a teenager--

00:02:24.910 --> 00:02:25.750 align:middle line:90%
I said, ugh!

00:02:25.750 --> 00:02:27.220 align:middle line:90%
Dad, that's easy for you to say.

00:02:27.220 --> 00:02:29.380 align:middle line:84%
You were born that
way, but I wasn't.

00:02:29.380 --> 00:02:30.260 align:middle line:90%
What do I do?

00:02:30.260 --> 00:02:32.260 align:middle line:84%
And he looked at me and
he said four more words.

00:02:32.260 --> 00:02:35.140 align:middle line:90%
He said, honey, I don't know.

00:02:35.140 --> 00:02:38.000 align:middle line:84%
And I set my life about
to find out that answer

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:38.800 align:middle line:90%
to that question.

00:02:38.800 --> 00:02:40.480 align:middle line:90%
How can I be happy?

00:02:40.480 --> 00:02:42.790 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: What a beautiful dad.

00:02:42.790 --> 00:02:43.868 align:middle line:90%
What a beautiful dad.

00:02:43.868 --> 00:02:45.160 align:middle line:90%
And you know, it's interesting.

00:02:45.160 --> 00:02:47.920 align:middle line:84%
Because some parents would
look at a child like that

00:02:47.920 --> 00:02:50.080 align:middle line:84%
and medicate them
or think they need

00:02:50.080 --> 00:02:52.180 align:middle line:84%
to be on antidepressants
or so forth.

00:02:52.180 --> 00:02:56.630 align:middle line:84%
And you worked this out through
love and through perseverance.

00:02:56.630 --> 00:02:57.430 align:middle line:90%
You really did.

00:02:57.430 --> 00:02:57.890 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: I did.

00:02:57.890 --> 00:02:59.950 align:middle line:84%
I've been through a lot
of experimenting with,

00:02:59.950 --> 00:03:02.950 align:middle line:90%
what's going to make me happier?

00:03:02.950 --> 00:03:04.240 align:middle line:90%
I did do a lot of things.

00:03:04.240 --> 00:03:06.400 align:middle line:84%
I was very fortunate
that I started

00:03:06.400 --> 00:03:08.230 align:middle line:90%
meditating as a teenager.

00:03:08.230 --> 00:03:11.980 align:middle line:84%
That was a huge influence for
me when I started meditating.

00:03:11.980 --> 00:03:15.870 align:middle line:84%
I remember right away,
something lifted.

00:03:15.870 --> 00:03:18.040 align:middle line:84%
So one layer of
the clouds lifted

00:03:18.040 --> 00:03:19.675 align:middle line:90%
when I started meditating.

00:03:19.675 --> 00:03:21.520 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Why do
you think that is?

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:22.870 align:middle line:90%
How did you start meditating?

00:03:22.870 --> 00:03:25.130 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: I started
meditating when I was about 16.

00:03:25.130 --> 00:03:25.930 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:03:25.930 --> 00:03:29.770 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And so how
did you get into that?

00:03:29.770 --> 00:03:33.040 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: Because I had
been sort of unhappy,

00:03:33.040 --> 00:03:34.670 align:middle line:90%
I was searching for everything.

00:03:34.670 --> 00:03:39.300 align:middle line:84%
And this was back in
the '70s, early '70s.

00:03:39.300 --> 00:03:41.800 align:middle line:84%
I was growing up in California,
there was lots of cool stuff

00:03:41.800 --> 00:03:42.610 align:middle line:90%
available.

00:03:42.610 --> 00:03:45.490 align:middle line:84%
And I came across this
meditation, and I just--

00:03:45.490 --> 00:03:47.450 align:middle line:90%
something inside me said, that.

00:03:47.450 --> 00:03:48.250 align:middle line:90%
Do that.

00:03:48.250 --> 00:03:49.340 align:middle line:90%
And so I did.

00:03:49.340 --> 00:03:50.920 align:middle line:90%
And it really, really--

00:03:50.920 --> 00:03:52.800 align:middle line:84%
that was the first
thing that was lifted--

00:03:52.800 --> 00:03:53.925 align:middle line:90%
a layer of the unhappiness.

00:03:53.925 --> 00:03:56.770 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And now we know all
about meditation increasing

00:03:56.770 --> 00:03:59.230 align:middle line:84%
serotonin, and
dopamine, and all of

00:03:59.230 --> 00:04:01.420 align:middle line:90%
these great neurotransmitters.

00:04:01.420 --> 00:04:04.460 align:middle line:84%
And you experimented with that
and learned that on your own,

00:04:04.460 --> 00:04:05.260 align:middle line:90%
which is amazing.

00:04:05.260 --> 00:04:06.060 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: Yeah.

00:04:06.060 --> 00:04:09.190 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And then you wound up
at the Maharishi Institute--

00:04:09.190 --> 00:04:10.750 align:middle line:90%
or The University of Maharishi.

00:04:10.750 --> 00:04:11.550 align:middle line:90%
What is that?

00:04:11.550 --> 00:04:11.710 align:middle line:90%


00:04:11.710 --> 00:04:13.627 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: Maharishi
University of Management.

00:04:13.627 --> 00:04:18.370 align:middle line:84%
So I was 17 years old and
ready to go to college.

00:04:18.370 --> 00:04:20.290 align:middle line:84%
And I told my
parents that I wanted

00:04:20.290 --> 00:04:22.570 align:middle line:84%
to go to this college,
where everybody meditated.

00:04:22.570 --> 00:04:24.640 align:middle line:84%
Everybody did
transcendental meditation--

00:04:24.640 --> 00:04:27.880 align:middle line:84%
the staff, the students,
and all the teachers.

00:04:27.880 --> 00:04:31.300 align:middle line:84%
And they thought
it was kind of--

00:04:31.300 --> 00:04:32.410 align:middle line:90%
not usual.

00:04:32.410 --> 00:04:33.370 align:middle line:90%
It wasn't usual.

00:04:33.370 --> 00:04:34.052 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It wasn't mainstream.

00:04:34.052 --> 00:04:36.302 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: And they said,
oh, we'll go for a semester,

00:04:36.302 --> 00:04:38.470 align:middle line:84%
and then they figured
I would never stay.

00:04:38.470 --> 00:04:40.960 align:middle line:84%
It was in Iowa, so, yeah,
I'm not going to stay.

00:04:40.960 --> 00:04:43.780 align:middle line:84%
And I went there, and
I felt like I was home.

00:04:43.780 --> 00:04:45.770 align:middle line:84%
And it was
consciousness-based education.

00:04:45.770 --> 00:04:49.780 align:middle line:84%
So it wasn't just about
learning about chemistry,

00:04:49.780 --> 00:04:52.120 align:middle line:90%
or physics, or art.

00:04:52.120 --> 00:04:54.340 align:middle line:84%
Actually, everything
was tied together

00:04:54.340 --> 00:04:56.500 align:middle line:84%
with this field of study
called the "science

00:04:56.500 --> 00:04:58.750 align:middle line:84%
of creative intelligence,"
which is basically studying

00:04:58.750 --> 00:05:01.090 align:middle line:84%
the laws of nature, the
laws of the universe,

00:05:01.090 --> 00:05:02.410 align:middle line:90%
the universal principles.

00:05:02.410 --> 00:05:05.560 align:middle line:84%
And every subject tied
back to that science

00:05:05.560 --> 00:05:06.850 align:middle line:90%
of creative intelligence.

00:05:06.850 --> 00:05:09.220 align:middle line:84%
And every day, all the staff,
students, and teachers,

00:05:09.220 --> 00:05:12.490 align:middle line:84%
we were meditating twice
a day, and it was really

00:05:12.490 --> 00:05:14.830 align:middle line:84%
about developing your
consciousness along

00:05:14.830 --> 00:05:19.390 align:middle line:84%
with learning the
objective kinds of--

00:05:19.390 --> 00:05:20.810 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: How ahead of its time!

00:05:20.810 --> 00:05:21.610 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: Totally.

00:05:21.610 --> 00:05:22.910 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It was so
ahead of its time,

00:05:22.910 --> 00:05:23.995 align:middle line:90%
and it's still around today?

00:05:23.995 --> 00:05:24.795 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: It is.

00:05:24.795 --> 00:05:27.970 align:middle line:84%
It's a fully accredited
university to the PhD level.

00:05:27.970 --> 00:05:31.630 align:middle line:84%
And for me, it was
just exactly what

00:05:31.630 --> 00:05:34.420 align:middle line:84%
I needed because I
also was with people

00:05:34.420 --> 00:05:38.890 align:middle line:84%
who cared about something
deeper than most

00:05:38.890 --> 00:05:41.920 align:middle line:84%
of the superficial things that
people care about in college.

00:05:41.920 --> 00:05:45.760 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yeah, and then it
gave you a deeper experience.

00:05:45.760 --> 00:05:48.060 align:middle line:84%
Did you always have
an affinity for India?

00:05:48.060 --> 00:05:49.050 align:middle line:90%
Or was it just--

00:05:49.050 --> 00:05:49.850 align:middle line:90%
did you?

00:05:49.850 --> 00:05:52.680 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: I did--

00:05:52.680 --> 00:05:54.600 align:middle line:84%
Because I started
meditating at a young age,

00:05:54.600 --> 00:05:56.850 align:middle line:84%
I felt a real deep
affinity with India.

00:05:56.850 --> 00:06:02.050 align:middle line:84%
And I actually went to
India a number of times.

00:06:02.050 --> 00:06:06.360 align:middle line:84%
Most recently I went
for my 60th birthday

00:06:06.360 --> 00:06:09.000 align:middle line:84%
and ended up having
a second wedding

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:11.735 align:middle line:84%
ceremony with my husband,
which is a wild story.

00:06:11.735 --> 00:06:12.610 align:middle line:90%
I don't know if you--

00:06:12.610 --> 00:06:12.990 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah!

00:06:12.990 --> 00:06:15.407 align:middle line:84%
I'd love to hear it because
the pictures are so beautiful.

00:06:15.407 --> 00:06:16.260 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: Yeah.

00:06:16.260 --> 00:06:22.680 align:middle line:84%
So, many years ago, actually at
this point almost 20 years ago,

00:06:22.680 --> 00:06:24.918 align:middle line:90%
I was 39 and I was not married.

00:06:24.918 --> 00:06:26.460 align:middle line:84%
I was single, had
never been married,

00:06:26.460 --> 00:06:28.200 align:middle line:84%
and really wanted
to get married.

00:06:28.200 --> 00:06:31.200 align:middle line:84%
And I went and had a
Vedic astrology reading.

00:06:31.200 --> 00:06:34.380 align:middle line:84%
Vedic astrology is the
astrology of East India.

00:06:34.380 --> 00:06:36.840 align:middle line:84%
And the astrologers told
me all about my life.

00:06:36.840 --> 00:06:38.620 align:middle line:90%
It was so accurate.

00:06:38.620 --> 00:06:40.920 align:middle line:84%
And then he said,
oh, everything's

00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:43.290 align:middle line:84%
great in your life, except
you want to get married.

00:06:43.290 --> 00:06:44.490 align:middle line:90%
And I said, yeah!

00:06:44.490 --> 00:06:45.990 align:middle line:90%
He said, well, let me tell you.

00:06:45.990 --> 00:06:48.630 align:middle line:84%
Over the next three months,
you're going to meet three men,

00:06:48.630 --> 00:06:50.700 align:middle line:84%
they're all foreign,
and not one of them

00:06:50.700 --> 00:06:53.808 align:middle line:84%
is going to be your life
partner, your soul mate.

00:06:53.808 --> 00:06:55.350 align:middle line:84%
And I said, well,
that never happens.

00:06:55.350 --> 00:06:57.463 align:middle line:90%
I never meet three men in a row.

00:06:57.463 --> 00:06:59.880 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I can go years without
meeting an interesting guy.

00:06:59.880 --> 00:07:01.207 align:middle line:90%
And he said, no, it'll happen.

00:07:01.207 --> 00:07:03.540 align:middle line:84%
And then he said, and the
fourth man that'll come along,

00:07:03.540 --> 00:07:04.620 align:middle line:90%
he's your husband.

00:07:04.620 --> 00:07:06.000 align:middle line:90%
Let me describe him to you.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:07.230 align:middle line:90%
He'll have dark hair.

00:07:07.230 --> 00:07:08.460 align:middle line:90%
He'll be Mediterranean.

00:07:08.460 --> 00:07:11.980 align:middle line:84%
He will have been born
and raised in Italy.

00:07:11.980 --> 00:07:13.980 align:middle line:90%
He'll love dance and music.

00:07:13.980 --> 00:07:16.080 align:middle line:90%
And he will be a therapist.

00:07:16.080 --> 00:07:17.960 align:middle line:84%
And he will be six
years younger than you.

00:07:17.960 --> 00:07:18.760 align:middle line:90%
At which point.

00:07:18.760 --> 00:07:20.040 align:middle line:90%
I said, that's impossible.

00:07:20.040 --> 00:07:21.840 align:middle line:90%
I never date younger men.

00:07:21.840 --> 00:07:23.000 align:middle line:90%
He said, I can't help it.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:23.810 align:middle line:90%
He's your destiny.

00:07:23.810 --> 00:07:24.690 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: The detail!

00:07:24.690 --> 00:07:26.377 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: The detail of that.

00:07:26.377 --> 00:07:28.710 align:middle line:84%
And over the next three months,
I met three foreign men,

00:07:28.710 --> 00:07:30.660 align:middle line:90%
one right after another.

00:07:30.660 --> 00:07:32.220 align:middle line:84%
Two of them are
still dear friends.

00:07:32.220 --> 00:07:34.080 align:middle line:84%
And then I forgot
about that reading.

00:07:34.080 --> 00:07:35.790 align:middle line:84%
And then nine months
later, Lisa, I

00:07:35.790 --> 00:07:38.580 align:middle line:84%
was at the Omega
Institute in New York--

00:07:38.580 --> 00:07:39.930 align:middle line:90%
big, big campus.

00:07:39.930 --> 00:07:42.330 align:middle line:90%
I was there for a workshop.

00:07:42.330 --> 00:07:45.880 align:middle line:84%
And I arrived-- as I pulled
into the parking lot,

00:07:45.880 --> 00:07:48.367 align:middle line:84%
there's a woman
getting into her car--

00:07:48.367 --> 00:07:49.950 align:middle line:84%
big parking lot,
lots of cars, a woman

00:07:49.950 --> 00:07:51.300 align:middle line:90%
getting in her car to leave.

00:07:51.300 --> 00:07:52.758 align:middle line:84%
And I had been
there a year earlier

00:07:52.758 --> 00:07:55.042 align:middle line:84%
and befriended one
person, and that was her.

00:07:55.042 --> 00:07:56.250 align:middle line:90%
And she's getting in her car.

00:07:56.250 --> 00:07:58.020 align:middle line:84%
I say, Kathleen,
what are you doing?

00:07:58.020 --> 00:07:58.820 align:middle line:90%
How are you doing?

00:07:58.820 --> 00:08:00.700 align:middle line:84%
She said, oh, I just
got off of a course.

00:08:00.700 --> 00:08:01.500 align:middle line:90%
And I'm leaving.

00:08:01.500 --> 00:08:02.930 align:middle line:84%
But do you want to
still meet a guy?

00:08:02.930 --> 00:08:03.805 align:middle line:90%
Are you still single?

00:08:03.805 --> 00:08:04.720 align:middle line:90%
I said, yeah.

00:08:04.720 --> 00:08:06.090 align:middle line:84%
She said, well, there
was a guy on my course.

00:08:06.090 --> 00:08:07.382 align:middle line:90%
And I think you might like him.

00:08:07.382 --> 00:08:08.510 align:middle line:90%
Do you like big macho guys?

00:08:08.510 --> 00:08:09.310 align:middle line:90%
And I said, yeah.

00:08:09.310 --> 00:08:11.820 align:middle line:90%
She said, well, he's not that.

00:08:11.820 --> 00:08:13.930 align:middle line:84%
Then, she said, do
you like older men?

00:08:13.930 --> 00:08:14.730 align:middle line:90%
I said, yeah!

00:08:14.730 --> 00:08:15.980 align:middle line:90%
She said, well, he's not that.

00:08:15.980 --> 00:08:17.440 align:middle line:90%
I think he's younger than you.

00:08:17.440 --> 00:08:18.750 align:middle line:84%
And I said, well, I don't
really want to meet him,

00:08:18.750 --> 00:08:19.680 align:middle line:90%
I don't think.

00:08:19.680 --> 00:08:21.060 align:middle line:90%
Just as I said that, she turned.

00:08:21.060 --> 00:08:24.120 align:middle line:84%
And across the other end of the
parking lot, Sergio is walking.

00:08:24.120 --> 00:08:25.710 align:middle line:90%
She said, there he is.

00:08:25.710 --> 00:08:27.180 align:middle line:90%
I looked at his energy.

00:08:27.180 --> 00:08:28.860 align:middle line:84%
And I said, I've
got to meet him.

00:08:28.860 --> 00:08:31.610 align:middle line:84%
And she walked me over to
him and introduced me to him.

00:08:31.610 --> 00:08:33.360 align:middle line:84%
They'd just gotten off
of a dance workshop

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:35.700 align:middle line:84%
and before he said hello
to me, he danced me

00:08:35.700 --> 00:08:36.992 align:middle line:90%
around this gravel parking lot.

00:08:36.992 --> 00:08:37.792 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: What?

00:08:37.792 --> 00:08:39.250 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: I looked in his eyes.

00:08:39.250 --> 00:08:41.190 align:middle line:84%
And I said, that's
my life partner.

00:08:41.190 --> 00:08:45.080 align:middle line:84%
And he is born and raised
in Italy, dark hair,

00:08:45.080 --> 00:08:47.970 align:middle line:84%
loves dance and
music, is a therapist,

00:08:47.970 --> 00:08:49.440 align:middle line:84%
and is six years
younger than I am.

00:08:49.440 --> 00:08:50.823 align:middle line:90%
We've been together ever since.

00:08:50.823 --> 00:08:51.990 align:middle line:90%
And we got married in India.

00:08:51.990 --> 00:08:53.153 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That is amazing.

00:08:53.153 --> 00:08:54.820 align:middle line:84%
You got married in
India the first time,

00:08:54.820 --> 00:08:56.830 align:middle line:84%
and you went back and
renewed your vows?

00:08:56.830 --> 00:08:57.830 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: That's right.

00:08:57.830 --> 00:08:59.190 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's beautiful.

00:08:59.190 --> 00:09:02.070 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: For those people who
are single, I have to tell you,

00:09:02.070 --> 00:09:05.110 align:middle line:84%
good Vedic astrology
can be really accurate.

00:09:05.110 --> 00:09:05.910 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It can.

00:09:05.910 --> 00:09:07.688 align:middle line:84%
And you've always been
a believer in that,

00:09:07.688 --> 00:09:09.230 align:middle line:84%
and it's always
worked for your life.

00:09:09.230 --> 00:09:10.050 align:middle line:90%
It's interesting.

00:09:10.050 --> 00:09:12.930 align:middle line:84%
Some people adhere
to certain schools,

00:09:12.930 --> 00:09:14.930 align:middle line:84%
and that really just
works for your life.

00:09:14.930 --> 00:09:16.230 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: I've seen it.

00:09:16.230 --> 00:09:18.930 align:middle line:84%
I've seen it work so
many times it's shocking.

00:09:18.930 --> 00:09:22.050 align:middle line:84%
I mean, in 1990, I was
told that in 1996 I'd

00:09:22.050 --> 00:09:24.730 align:middle line:84%
have a best-selling book,
and I thought he was crazy.

00:09:24.730 --> 00:09:26.400 align:middle line:90%
I didn't even like writing.

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:29.475 align:middle line:84%
And sure enough,
in September 1996,

00:09:29.475 --> 00:09:31.350 align:middle line:84%
my first book came out
and went to number one

00:09:31.350 --> 00:09:32.475 align:middle line:90%
on the New York Times list.

00:09:32.475 --> 00:09:33.280 align:middle line:90%
So it's all in--

00:09:33.280 --> 00:09:34.155 align:middle line:90%
I mean, it's bizarre.

00:09:34.155 --> 00:09:35.070 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I love it.

00:09:35.070 --> 00:09:37.890 align:middle line:84%
I love that you have this much
guidance, and you trust it.

00:09:37.890 --> 00:09:40.610 align:middle line:84%
So how did you get into
writing about happiness?

00:09:40.610 --> 00:09:42.360 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it was a
lifelong journey for you.

00:09:42.360 --> 00:09:45.190 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: Yes, yes.

00:09:45.190 --> 00:09:48.640 align:middle line:84%
Lisa, when I was not happy, in
my early 20s, I was meditating,

00:09:48.640 --> 00:09:51.660 align:middle line:84%
but still I wasn't feeling
the deep happiness I wanted.

00:09:51.660 --> 00:09:53.590 align:middle line:90%
I did what a lot of people do.

00:09:53.590 --> 00:09:55.832 align:middle line:90%
I set five goals for myself.

00:09:55.832 --> 00:09:56.790 align:middle line:90%
I set goals for myself.

00:09:56.790 --> 00:09:58.525 align:middle line:90%
And for me, it was five goals.

00:09:58.525 --> 00:10:00.900 align:middle line:84%
And I'll share them with you
because I think a lot of you

00:10:00.900 --> 00:10:02.050 align:middle line:84%
might be able to
relate to these.

00:10:02.050 --> 00:10:03.030 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, yes.

00:10:03.030 --> 00:10:05.550 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: I thought, this is
what I needed to be happy--

00:10:05.550 --> 00:10:10.980 align:middle line:84%
a great career helping people,
a wonderful life partner,

00:10:10.980 --> 00:10:15.450 align:middle line:84%
fabulous friends, a
comfortable home, and the fifth

00:10:15.450 --> 00:10:18.810 align:middle line:84%
was the equivalent of
Halle Berry's body.

00:10:18.810 --> 00:10:20.413 align:middle line:90%
Now I have four out of the five.

00:10:20.413 --> 00:10:22.830 align:middle line:84%
I don't have Halle Berry's
body, but I have a healthy body

00:10:22.830 --> 00:10:24.420 align:middle line:90%
for which I'm grateful.

00:10:24.420 --> 00:10:27.870 align:middle line:84%
And so I really worked
hard, like a lot of people

00:10:27.870 --> 00:10:30.180 align:middle line:84%
do, trying to get
all my ducks in a row

00:10:30.180 --> 00:10:33.240 align:middle line:90%
so that I would really be happy.

00:10:33.240 --> 00:10:35.880 align:middle line:90%
And I accomplished those things.

00:10:35.880 --> 00:10:36.995 align:middle line:90%
I had a great career.

00:10:36.995 --> 00:10:37.870 align:middle line:90%
I was helping people.

00:10:37.870 --> 00:10:39.030 align:middle line:90%
I had a great partner.

00:10:39.030 --> 00:10:42.090 align:middle line:84%
I had lots of great
things happening for me.

00:10:42.090 --> 00:10:49.437 align:middle line:84%
And one day, in June of 1998, I
had three books in the top five

00:10:49.437 --> 00:10:51.020 align:middle line:84%
on the New York Times
bestseller list.

00:10:51.020 --> 00:10:51.820 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:10:51.820 --> 00:10:55.070 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: I had just given
a speech to 8,000 people.

00:10:55.070 --> 00:10:58.400 align:middle line:90%
I had autographed 5,432 books.

00:10:58.400 --> 00:11:00.860 align:middle line:84%
My client had a massage
therapist massaging my hand

00:11:00.860 --> 00:11:02.690 align:middle line:90%
so I could keep on signing.

00:11:02.690 --> 00:11:04.970 align:middle line:90%
I felt like an author rock star.

00:11:04.970 --> 00:11:07.830 align:middle line:84%
And at the end of
signing that last book,

00:11:07.830 --> 00:11:09.290 align:middle line:84%
I went up to my
hotel room, which

00:11:09.290 --> 00:11:12.385 align:middle line:84%
was the penthouse suite that
my client had gotten for me.

00:11:12.385 --> 00:11:13.760 align:middle line:84%
And I walked over
to the windows.

00:11:13.760 --> 00:11:16.670 align:middle line:84%
There were these beautiful
windows with a panoramic view

00:11:16.670 --> 00:11:18.230 align:middle line:90%
of Chicago.

00:11:18.230 --> 00:11:21.380 align:middle line:84%
And I looked out the
window, and I turned around,

00:11:21.380 --> 00:11:24.590 align:middle line:84%
and I fell onto the bed,
and I burst into tears.

00:11:24.590 --> 00:11:26.990 align:middle line:84%
And I burst into tears
because I realized

00:11:26.990 --> 00:11:29.090 align:middle line:84%
I had everything I
thought I needed,

00:11:29.090 --> 00:11:31.430 align:middle line:90%
and I still wasn't happy.

00:11:31.430 --> 00:11:33.770 align:middle line:84%
And I could no
longer fool myself

00:11:33.770 --> 00:11:36.590 align:middle line:84%
into thinking that
just the next thing was

00:11:36.590 --> 00:11:38.120 align:middle line:90%
going to make me happy.

00:11:38.120 --> 00:11:40.190 align:middle line:84%
It was kind of the end
of the road for me.

00:11:40.190 --> 00:11:42.840 align:middle line:84%
And that's when I decided,
no matter what I did,

00:11:42.840 --> 00:11:46.090 align:middle line:84%
I was going to find
out how to be happy.

00:11:46.090 --> 00:11:48.410 align:middle line:84%
And I pretty much
dropped what I was doing,

00:11:48.410 --> 00:11:50.600 align:middle line:84%
and I started researching
all the happiness

00:11:50.600 --> 00:11:51.470 align:middle line:90%
experts out there.

00:11:51.470 --> 00:11:55.100 align:middle line:84%
And I interviewed what I called
unconditionally happy people.

00:11:55.100 --> 00:11:57.950 align:middle line:84%
I've interviewed hundreds of
unconditionally happy people.

00:11:57.950 --> 00:12:01.080 align:middle line:84%
And I started doing
what they did.

00:12:01.080 --> 00:12:03.710 align:middle line:84%
And within a short
period of time,

00:12:03.710 --> 00:12:05.250 align:middle line:90%
it totally changed my happiness.

00:12:05.250 --> 00:12:07.400 align:middle line:84%
I would say, back then,
I was maybe a D plus

00:12:07.400 --> 00:12:08.900 align:middle line:84%
if you were grading
me in happiness.

00:12:08.900 --> 00:12:11.112 align:middle line:84%
And now, I'm a solid A.
I still am working at it.

00:12:11.112 --> 00:12:12.070 align:middle line:90%
I'm a work in progress.

00:12:12.070 --> 00:12:16.350 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: No, it's such an
epidemic for so many people.

00:12:16.350 --> 00:12:18.020 align:middle line:84%
And we have depression
as an epidemic.

00:12:18.020 --> 00:12:20.780 align:middle line:84%
And there are not
a lot of solutions

00:12:20.780 --> 00:12:24.410 align:middle line:84%
other than medication, as it
being a chemicals situation.

00:12:24.410 --> 00:12:25.940 align:middle line:84%
Even if you're on
the medication,

00:12:25.940 --> 00:12:30.740 align:middle line:84%
you need something else that
gives you practical tools

00:12:30.740 --> 00:12:33.980 align:middle line:84%
to enhance your
quality of happiness.

00:12:33.980 --> 00:12:34.790 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: Totally.

00:12:34.790 --> 00:12:36.920 align:middle line:84%
You know, here's what
I found is that we do.

00:12:36.920 --> 00:12:39.330 align:middle line:84%
We have an epidemic of
unhappiness in our society.

00:12:39.330 --> 00:12:42.560 align:middle line:84%
One out of four women
is on anti-depressants.

00:12:42.560 --> 00:12:43.520 align:middle line:90%
That's a lot.

00:12:43.520 --> 00:12:46.370 align:middle line:84%
We have more than we've
ever had as a society,

00:12:46.370 --> 00:12:48.380 align:middle line:90%
and we're unhappier than ever.

00:12:48.380 --> 00:12:50.400 align:middle line:90%
So that's the bad news.

00:12:50.400 --> 00:12:51.810 align:middle line:90%
But there's good news.

00:12:51.810 --> 00:12:54.320 align:middle line:84%
And the good news is
that science has actually

00:12:54.320 --> 00:12:56.480 align:middle line:90%
cracked the happiness code.

00:12:56.480 --> 00:12:59.562 align:middle line:84%
We know what it takes
for people to be happier.

00:12:59.562 --> 00:13:01.520 align:middle line:84%
You know, I think that
should be headline news.

00:13:01.520 --> 00:13:02.590 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, we do.

00:13:02.590 --> 00:13:04.580 align:middle line:90%


00:13:04.580 --> 00:13:06.380 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: And it's simple.

00:13:06.380 --> 00:13:09.740 align:middle line:84%
So I know we're going to get
to share some of the things

00:13:09.740 --> 00:13:12.330 align:middle line:84%
with everybody about how to
raise their happiness level.

00:13:12.330 --> 00:13:13.130 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, yes.

00:13:13.130 --> 00:13:14.755 align:middle line:84%
First, let's take a
look here at Marci,

00:13:14.755 --> 00:13:16.970 align:middle line:84%
talking about your
happiness set point.

00:13:16.970 --> 00:13:18.100 align:middle line:90%
Take a look.

00:13:18.100 --> 00:13:19.670 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: The
happiness set point

00:13:19.670 --> 00:13:24.470 align:middle line:84%
says that no matter what
happens to us, whether it's

00:13:24.470 --> 00:13:28.440 align:middle line:84%
good or bad, we will tend to
return to our happiness set

00:13:28.440 --> 00:13:29.240 align:middle line:90%
point.

00:13:29.240 --> 00:13:31.220 align:middle line:90%
It's like a thermostat setting.

00:13:31.220 --> 00:13:35.030 align:middle line:10%
No matter what we do,
unless we consciously

00:13:35.030 --> 00:13:37.370 align:middle line:10%
change that
thermostat setting, we

00:13:37.370 --> 00:13:41.660 align:middle line:10%
will hover around that happiness
set point, which explains,

00:13:41.660 --> 00:13:44.803 align:middle line:10%
by the way, why people
who win the lottery--

00:13:44.803 --> 00:13:46.220 align:middle line:10%
you think, oh I'd
win the lottery.

00:13:46.220 --> 00:13:47.730 align:middle line:90%
I'd be so happy.

00:13:47.730 --> 00:13:51.080 align:middle line:84%
Well, you would be
happier for a few months.

00:13:51.080 --> 00:13:53.660 align:middle line:84%
Within a year, you
will tend to return

00:13:53.660 --> 00:13:56.480 align:middle line:84%
to your original
happiness set point.

00:13:56.480 --> 00:13:59.810 align:middle line:10%
We actually saw an
extraordinary example of this

00:13:59.810 --> 00:14:02.830 align:middle line:10%
earlier this morning--

00:14:02.830 --> 00:14:05.320 align:middle line:10%
the most extreme situation
that you could possibly

00:14:05.320 --> 00:14:07.852 align:middle line:10%
imagine that Elizabeth had.

00:14:07.852 --> 00:14:10.060 align:middle line:84%
And I don't know that it
was certainly within a year,

00:14:10.060 --> 00:14:16.490 align:middle line:84%
but within time, she returned
to her happiness set point.

00:14:16.490 --> 00:14:20.020 align:middle line:84%
So the happiness set point
is the key to our happiness,

00:14:20.020 --> 00:14:21.490 align:middle line:90%
and here's how it's determined.

00:14:21.490 --> 00:14:23.230 align:middle line:90%
It is 50% genetic.

00:14:23.230 --> 00:14:24.440 align:middle line:90%
We're born with it.

00:14:24.440 --> 00:14:28.680 align:middle line:84%
I did not get the
good genes on that.

00:14:28.680 --> 00:14:30.510 align:middle line:84%
My mother's genes were
not the happy genes,

00:14:30.510 --> 00:14:32.580 align:middle line:84%
but my mother has a
great success story.

00:14:32.580 --> 00:14:34.990 align:middle line:10%
She did get happy after
I did all this research.

00:14:34.990 --> 00:14:37.560 align:middle line:10%
She was my Guinea pig,
and she was in her 70s,

00:14:37.560 --> 00:14:39.310 align:middle line:10%
and she got really,
really happy.

00:14:39.310 --> 00:14:41.490 align:middle line:10%
It was kind of a
miracle, actually.

00:14:41.490 --> 00:14:44.040 align:middle line:10%
So it's 50% genetic.

00:14:44.040 --> 00:14:47.820 align:middle line:10%
It's 10% your circumstances,
such a tiny piece of the pie

00:14:47.820 --> 00:14:50.070 align:middle line:10%
and yet that's what
everybody is trying to chase

00:14:50.070 --> 00:14:52.980 align:middle line:10%
after to make themselves happy.

00:14:52.980 --> 00:14:56.560 align:middle line:84%
The other 40% is your habits
of thoughts and behavior.

00:14:56.560 --> 00:14:59.130 align:middle line:10%
Now that's what we can really
do a lot about to influence

00:14:59.130 --> 00:15:00.390 align:middle line:10%
our happiness.

00:15:00.390 --> 00:15:03.180 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to take
this a step further.

00:15:03.180 --> 00:15:07.200 align:middle line:84%
Researchers in the field of
epigenetics studying our genes

00:15:07.200 --> 00:15:13.530 align:middle line:84%
have said that our genes can
be influenced by our habits.

00:15:13.530 --> 00:15:17.310 align:middle line:84%
That means that 90% of
our happiness set point

00:15:17.310 --> 00:15:20.880 align:middle line:84%
can be impacted by
changing our habits.

00:15:20.880 --> 00:15:22.100 align:middle line:90%
That's huge.

00:15:22.100 --> 00:15:22.900 align:middle line:90%
That really is.

00:15:22.900 --> 00:15:26.010 align:middle line:84%
And that's why I'm passionate
about this and about teaching

00:15:26.010 --> 00:15:27.010 align:middle line:90%
this to children.

00:15:27.010 --> 00:15:28.730 align:middle line:84%
So if you have children
or grandchildren,

00:15:28.730 --> 00:15:30.090 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to share
with you some things

00:15:30.090 --> 00:15:32.760 align:middle line:84%
today that I want you to take
home, and show them, and share

00:15:32.760 --> 00:15:34.170 align:middle line:90%
with them.

00:15:34.170 --> 00:15:36.420 align:middle line:84%
So people always ask me,
well, Marci, what do you mean

00:15:36.420 --> 00:15:37.628 align:middle line:90%
by being happy for no reason?

00:15:37.628 --> 00:15:39.600 align:middle line:84%
Does that mean that
you're walking around 24/7

00:15:39.600 --> 00:15:40.892 align:middle line:90%
with a silly grin on your face?

00:15:40.892 --> 00:15:43.140 align:middle line:84%
You're just happy no
matter what goes on?

00:15:43.140 --> 00:15:44.890 align:middle line:90%
That is not what I mean.

00:15:44.890 --> 00:15:47.820 align:middle line:10%
Here's my definition of
being happy for no reason.

00:15:47.820 --> 00:15:50.940 align:middle line:10%
Happy for no reason
is an interstate

00:15:50.940 --> 00:15:53.280 align:middle line:10%
of peace and
well-being that doesn't

00:15:53.280 --> 00:15:56.220 align:middle line:10%
depend on our circumstances.

00:15:56.220 --> 00:15:58.740 align:middle line:84%
So, yeah, you might get
upset about something.

00:15:58.740 --> 00:16:00.240 align:middle line:84%
You might be afraid
about something.

00:16:00.240 --> 00:16:03.030 align:middle line:10%
You might be frustrated
about something.

00:16:03.030 --> 00:16:06.570 align:middle line:10%
And yet there is a
backdrop of an interstate

00:16:06.570 --> 00:16:08.070 align:middle line:10%
of peace and
well-being that doesn't

00:16:08.070 --> 00:16:11.106 align:middle line:10%
depend on your circumstances.

00:16:11.106 --> 00:16:16.040 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: OK, you interviewed
people that were happy.

00:16:16.040 --> 00:16:19.245 align:middle line:84%
What was the theme-- what
did they have in common?

00:16:19.245 --> 00:16:20.690 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: So a
couple of things.

00:16:20.690 --> 00:16:23.800 align:middle line:84%
First of all, what's so
cool is that no matter where

00:16:23.800 --> 00:16:27.880 align:middle line:84%
you are in your happiness
set point, wherever you are,

00:16:27.880 --> 00:16:28.930 align:middle line:90%
you can change it.

00:16:28.930 --> 00:16:31.500 align:middle line:84%
That, to me, is,
like, hallelujah.

00:16:31.500 --> 00:16:33.537 align:middle line:84%
And what I found
about happy people

00:16:33.537 --> 00:16:35.995 align:middle line:84%
is that the only difference
between them and everybody else

00:16:35.995 --> 00:16:37.870 align:middle line:84%
is that they have
different habits.

00:16:37.870 --> 00:16:41.620 align:middle line:84%
And so what they did is
they lived their lives

00:16:41.620 --> 00:16:44.500 align:middle line:84%
in the seven main areas
that we'll talk about.

00:16:44.500 --> 00:16:47.650 align:middle line:84%
They lived them in an
energy of expansion

00:16:47.650 --> 00:16:50.980 align:middle line:84%
rather than an energy
of contraction.

00:16:50.980 --> 00:16:53.050 align:middle line:84%
You know the whole
thing about, there's

00:16:53.050 --> 00:16:54.710 align:middle line:90%
two energies on the planet.

00:16:54.710 --> 00:16:58.420 align:middle line:84%
