00:24:22.330 --> 00:24:22.650 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:24:22.650 --> 00:24:23.490 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: You went weak.

00:24:23.490 --> 00:24:24.290 align:middle line:90%
Now three times.

00:24:24.290 --> 00:24:25.140 align:middle line:90%
I'm a good person.

00:24:25.140 --> 00:24:26.370 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I'm a good person.

00:24:26.370 --> 00:24:27.240 align:middle line:90%
I'm a good person.

00:24:27.240 --> 00:24:28.130 align:middle line:90%
I'm a good person.

00:24:28.130 --> 00:24:28.950 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: Arm out.

00:24:28.950 --> 00:24:29.800 align:middle line:90%
Stay strong.

00:24:29.800 --> 00:24:30.960 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, my goodness.

00:24:30.960 --> 00:24:32.585 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: I want to
show you one more.

00:24:32.585 --> 00:24:34.980 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:24:34.980 --> 00:24:38.130 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: You're a fabulous
mother to a beautiful daughter

00:24:38.130 --> 00:24:39.280 align:middle line:90%
Kayla, who I adore.

00:24:39.280 --> 00:24:40.695 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yeah, she
loves you, too.

00:24:40.695 --> 00:24:41.820 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: And she's great.

00:24:41.820 --> 00:24:45.630 align:middle line:84%
Now as a parent, my
suspicion is, at some point,

00:24:45.630 --> 00:24:48.150 align:middle line:84%
you've told her, honey,
don't use the word "can't."

00:24:48.150 --> 00:24:49.570 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, I have.

00:24:49.570 --> 00:24:50.370 align:middle line:90%
I have.

00:24:50.370 --> 00:24:52.680 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, that was a four-letter
word in our family.

00:24:52.680 --> 00:24:56.160 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: Well, this
is so cool to show kids.

00:24:56.160 --> 00:24:58.770 align:middle line:84%
Three times I want you to
say, I can't do a good job.

00:24:58.770 --> 00:25:00.540 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I can't do a good job.

00:25:00.540 --> 00:25:01.710 align:middle line:90%
I can't do a good job.

00:25:01.710 --> 00:25:02.850 align:middle line:90%
I can't do a good job.

00:25:02.850 --> 00:25:03.930 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: Arm out.

00:25:03.930 --> 00:25:05.020 align:middle line:90%
Stay strong.

00:25:05.020 --> 00:25:06.110 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Ugh!

00:25:06.110 --> 00:25:07.450 align:middle line:90%
No matter how hard I try.

00:25:07.450 --> 00:25:09.450 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: Now three
times, I can do a good job.

00:25:09.450 --> 00:25:10.440 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I can do a good job.

00:25:10.440 --> 00:25:11.307 align:middle line:90%
I can do a good job.

00:25:11.307 --> 00:25:12.140 align:middle line:90%
I can do a good job.

00:25:12.140 --> 00:25:13.307 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: Put your arm out.

00:25:13.307 --> 00:25:15.060 align:middle line:90%
Stay strong.

00:25:15.060 --> 00:25:15.960 align:middle line:90%
Isn't that great?

00:25:15.960 --> 00:25:16.760 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:25:16.760 --> 00:25:20.220 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: If you have kids, as
I told you, show this to them.

00:25:20.220 --> 00:25:22.860 align:middle line:90%
Because they so go, oh, my gosh.

00:25:22.860 --> 00:25:24.297 align:middle line:90%
It really proves a point.

00:25:24.297 --> 00:25:25.755 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: The power
of your thoughts.

00:25:25.755 --> 00:25:27.840 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: Absolutely.

00:25:27.840 --> 00:25:31.110 align:middle line:84%
And 80% of our thoughts in
a given day are negative,

00:25:31.110 --> 00:25:32.910 align:middle line:84%
and we wonder why
we're so exhausted

00:25:32.910 --> 00:25:34.410 align:middle line:90%
at the end of the day.

00:25:34.410 --> 00:25:36.290 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: We're constantly
pummeling ourselves.

00:25:36.290 --> 00:25:37.290 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: That's right.

00:25:37.290 --> 00:25:39.360 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And not giving
ourselves a fighting chance.

00:25:39.360 --> 00:25:40.360 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: That's right.

00:25:40.360 --> 00:25:43.020 align:middle line:84%
And what I found is that
happy people have learned

00:25:43.020 --> 00:25:45.540 align:middle line:90%
how to reverse that tendency.

00:25:45.540 --> 00:25:48.600 align:middle line:84%
I call it the Velcro
Teflon syndrome.

00:25:48.600 --> 00:25:52.560 align:middle line:84%
And what it means is our minds
are Velcro for the negative.

00:25:52.560 --> 00:25:54.180 align:middle line:90%
We just remember that negative.

00:25:54.180 --> 00:25:55.290 align:middle line:90%
It sticks to us.

00:25:55.290 --> 00:25:57.060 align:middle line:84%
And they're Teflon
for the positive.

00:25:57.060 --> 00:25:58.530 align:middle line:90%
The positive slide off of us.

00:25:58.530 --> 00:26:01.590 align:middle line:84%
You know, if you
get 10 compliments

00:26:01.590 --> 00:26:05.400 align:middle line:84%
in a day and one criticism,
you focus on that one negative.

00:26:05.400 --> 00:26:07.020 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's just
natural to do that.

00:26:07.020 --> 00:26:09.117 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: Because of
that negativity bias,

00:26:09.117 --> 00:26:10.950 align:middle line:84%
those 80% of our thoughts
that are negative,

00:26:10.950 --> 00:26:13.850 align:middle line:84%
we inherited that from
our caveman ancestors.

00:26:13.850 --> 00:26:16.790 align:middle line:90%
But happy people reverse that.

00:26:16.790 --> 00:26:20.030 align:middle line:84%
They actually Velcro
the positives,

00:26:20.030 --> 00:26:22.250 align:middle line:90%
and they Teflon the negatives.

00:26:22.250 --> 00:26:23.750 align:middle line:84%
And I'll give you
a couple of things

00:26:23.750 --> 00:26:27.440 align:middle line:84%
to do to Velcro those positives
that are so crazy simple

00:26:27.440 --> 00:26:29.550 align:middle line:84%
and you go, oh, that can't
possibly do anything.

00:26:29.550 --> 00:26:30.633 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I would love that.

00:26:30.633 --> 00:26:31.820 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: But it does.

00:26:31.820 --> 00:26:33.320 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I know
people like this that

00:26:33.320 --> 00:26:34.730 align:middle line:90%
are just happy for no reason.

00:26:34.730 --> 00:26:36.290 align:middle line:90%
They're just happy.

00:26:36.290 --> 00:26:38.630 align:middle line:90%
And I wonder how?

00:26:38.630 --> 00:26:40.880 align:middle line:84%
They have wonderful,
magical, miraculous lives.

00:26:40.880 --> 00:26:43.490 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: They have learned
to create neural pathways,

00:26:43.490 --> 00:26:45.740 align:middle line:84%
or they were born that way--
maybe their happiness set

00:26:45.740 --> 00:26:46.080 align:middle line:90%
point.

00:26:46.080 --> 00:26:47.080 align:middle line:90%
They were born that way.

00:26:47.080 --> 00:26:49.710 align:middle line:84%
But they've got neural
pathways for the positive.

00:26:49.710 --> 00:26:50.960 align:middle line:90%
And that's what we want to do.

00:26:50.960 --> 00:26:54.290 align:middle line:84%
We want to create the brain
circuitry for the positive.

00:26:54.290 --> 00:26:59.300 align:middle line:84%
Two crazy simple steps, the
first step is, look for it.

00:26:59.300 --> 00:27:01.130 align:middle line:90%
Be on the lookout.

00:27:01.130 --> 00:27:02.540 align:middle line:90%
Like, you're a detective.

00:27:02.540 --> 00:27:04.790 align:middle line:84%
You are on the
lookout for the good.

00:27:04.790 --> 00:27:07.220 align:middle line:84%
One of the women that
I interviewed for Happy

00:27:07.220 --> 00:27:10.790 align:middle line:84%
for No Reason, she pretends
that she's the Academy Awards

00:27:10.790 --> 00:27:11.690 align:middle line:90%
committee.

00:27:11.690 --> 00:27:16.520 align:middle line:84%
And every day her job is to
give out five Academy Awards.

00:27:16.520 --> 00:27:19.160 align:middle line:84%
So she's out for a
walk in the park,

00:27:19.160 --> 00:27:21.420 align:middle line:84%
and she sees a little
cute fluffy white dog.

00:27:21.420 --> 00:27:24.050 align:middle line:84%
And she goes, oh, that
dog gets my Academy Award

00:27:24.050 --> 00:27:26.390 align:middle line:90%
for the cutest dog of the day.

00:27:26.390 --> 00:27:29.030 align:middle line:84%
Maybe she'll go up to the
owner and tell the owner.

00:27:29.030 --> 00:27:30.530 align:middle line:84%
Or she doesn't even
have to do that,

00:27:30.530 --> 00:27:33.020 align:middle line:84%
but she's on the
lookout for the good.

00:27:33.020 --> 00:27:35.960 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: There's always
something to be grateful for.

00:27:35.960 --> 00:27:36.890 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: There is.

00:27:36.890 --> 00:27:40.400 align:middle line:84%
And it's just a matter of
practicing looking for it.

00:27:40.400 --> 00:27:44.480 align:middle line:84%
Then the second step
is to savor the good.

00:27:44.480 --> 00:27:48.980 align:middle line:84%
Research shows that it takes
20 seconds for the good things

00:27:48.980 --> 00:27:52.490 align:middle line:84%
to actually land and to start
creating new neural pathways

00:27:52.490 --> 00:27:53.810 align:middle line:90%
in the brain.

00:27:53.810 --> 00:27:56.715 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't take anywhere near
that long for the negatives

00:27:56.715 --> 00:27:57.515 align:middle line:90%
to get reinforced.

00:27:57.515 --> 00:27:58.315 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Really?

00:27:58.315 --> 00:28:00.740 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: But the
positives take 20 seconds.

00:28:00.740 --> 00:28:02.930 align:middle line:84%
So that means you've
got to actually sit

00:28:02.930 --> 00:28:06.290 align:middle line:84%
with that positive thing
and appreciate it rather

00:28:06.290 --> 00:28:08.418 align:middle line:90%
than sloughing it off.

00:28:08.418 --> 00:28:10.460 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I've heard that
you have to have at least

00:28:10.460 --> 00:28:13.208 align:middle line:84%
four positive
thoughts to counteract

00:28:13.208 --> 00:28:15.000 align:middle line:84%
the damage from every
one negative thought.

00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:15.800 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: You do.

00:28:15.800 --> 00:28:17.930 align:middle line:84%
And with the positive
ones, you need

00:28:17.930 --> 00:28:19.530 align:middle line:90%
to savor them for 20 seconds.

00:28:19.530 --> 00:28:21.290 align:middle line:84%
So if somebody gives
you a compliment,

00:28:21.290 --> 00:28:24.290 align:middle line:84%
they say, oh, you did a
great job on that project.

00:28:24.290 --> 00:28:27.140 align:middle line:84%
Instead of saying,
it was nothing,

00:28:27.140 --> 00:28:29.450 align:middle line:84%
when you knew you worked
really hard on it.

00:28:29.450 --> 00:28:32.240 align:middle line:84%
Or instead of saying,
oh, I had a lot of help,

00:28:32.240 --> 00:28:34.760 align:middle line:84%
you actually take
in the compliment.

00:28:34.760 --> 00:28:36.360 align:middle line:90%
And you say, thank you.

00:28:36.360 --> 00:28:38.420 align:middle line:84%
You know, I worked
really hard on that,

00:28:38.420 --> 00:28:40.220 align:middle line:84%
and I was happy with
how it turned out.

00:28:40.220 --> 00:28:42.770 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: sometimes
it's so hard to do.

00:28:42.770 --> 00:28:43.640 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: I know.

00:28:43.640 --> 00:28:45.110 align:middle line:90%
It's not the way we were taught.

00:28:45.110 --> 00:28:45.665 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It's counter-intuitive.

00:28:45.665 --> 00:28:47.748 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: It is, because
we think we're bragging.

00:28:47.748 --> 00:28:48.615 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:28:48.615 --> 00:28:49.490 align:middle line:90%
We need to be humble.

00:28:49.490 --> 00:28:51.530 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: Yeah,
it's not bragging.

00:28:51.530 --> 00:28:55.190 align:middle line:84%
It's actually just
owning what is good.

00:28:55.190 --> 00:28:57.020 align:middle line:84%
It's owning what's
good in your life.

00:28:57.020 --> 00:28:57.995 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Do you do this?

00:28:57.995 --> 00:28:59.420 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: I try to.

00:28:59.420 --> 00:29:01.130 align:middle line:90%
I'm not perfect.

00:29:01.130 --> 00:29:03.160 align:middle line:90%
But I do work on it, you know?

00:29:03.160 --> 00:29:05.630 align:middle line:84%
And if I'm having a
bad day, I go, OK,

00:29:05.630 --> 00:29:08.420 align:middle line:84%
time to give out five
Academy Awards and time

00:29:08.420 --> 00:29:13.010 align:middle line:84%
to stop and let that sunset
that's so beautiful sink in

00:29:13.010 --> 00:29:14.330 align:middle line:90%
for 20 seconds.

00:29:14.330 --> 00:29:17.300 align:middle line:84%
Because I know that when
it sinks in for 20 seconds,

00:29:17.300 --> 00:29:19.130 align:middle line:90%
I'm creating new brain circuits.

00:29:19.130 --> 00:29:20.360 align:middle line:90%
That's the whole point of it.

00:29:20.360 --> 00:29:22.250 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Do you
still see yourself

00:29:22.250 --> 00:29:23.750 align:middle line:84%
as that depressed
little girl that's

00:29:23.750 --> 00:29:25.430 align:middle line:90%
trying every day to be happy?

00:29:25.430 --> 00:29:26.540 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: I really don't.

00:29:26.540 --> 00:29:27.415 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Good for you.

00:29:27.415 --> 00:29:28.590 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: I really don't.

00:29:28.590 --> 00:29:31.370 align:middle line:90%
What I see is I see--

00:29:31.370 --> 00:29:35.330 align:middle line:84%
honestly, I feel gratitude
that that was my life journey

00:29:35.330 --> 00:29:38.090 align:middle line:84%
because I believe that
there are no accidents

00:29:38.090 --> 00:29:43.110 align:middle line:84%
and that I had a mission, a
calling, to teach happiness.

00:29:43.110 --> 00:29:45.620 align:middle line:84%
This is what I'm
on the planet for.

00:29:45.620 --> 00:29:49.290 align:middle line:84%
And I wouldn't have been able to
be anywhere near as effective,

00:29:49.290 --> 00:29:51.320 align:middle line:84%
I don't think, had I
just been born happy.

00:29:51.320 --> 00:29:52.500 align:middle line:84%
I would have been
like my dad and said,

00:29:52.500 --> 00:29:53.690 align:middle line:84%
I don't know what
to do to be happy.

00:29:53.690 --> 00:29:54.490 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:29:54.490 --> 00:29:57.340 align:middle line:84%
You would have gotten a regular
job and moved into the world.

00:29:57.340 --> 00:29:57.710 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: Yeah.

00:29:57.710 --> 00:29:59.585 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But this way
you're inspiring people.

00:29:59.585 --> 00:30:03.260 align:middle line:84%
How much of you fulfilling
this purpose and this passion

00:30:03.260 --> 00:30:07.115 align:middle line:84%
in your life has to do
with you being happy?

00:30:07.115 --> 00:30:10.100 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: You know,
I think we have

00:30:10.100 --> 00:30:12.110 align:middle line:90%
it backwards in our society.

00:30:12.110 --> 00:30:16.070 align:middle line:84%
We think that when
we are successful

00:30:16.070 --> 00:30:20.070 align:middle line:84%
or when we have all the things
in line, we will be happy.

00:30:20.070 --> 00:30:22.670 align:middle line:84%
It's actually that
happiness comes first,

00:30:22.670 --> 00:30:26.480 align:middle line:84%
and then we bring that more
to our passion in life.

00:30:26.480 --> 00:30:29.810 align:middle line:84%
You know, happy people, that
roof that I talked about?

00:30:29.810 --> 00:30:32.150 align:middle line:90%
That living an inspired life?

00:30:32.150 --> 00:30:35.960 align:middle line:84%
Happy people naturally
live an inspired life.

00:30:35.960 --> 00:30:38.240 align:middle line:90%
I'll give you an example.

00:30:38.240 --> 00:30:40.580 align:middle line:90%
My dad, the happy guy.

00:30:40.580 --> 00:30:42.690 align:middle line:90%
So my dad was a dentist.

00:30:42.690 --> 00:30:45.020 align:middle line:90%
And he loved being a dentist.

00:30:45.020 --> 00:30:46.140 align:middle line:90%
He loved it.

00:30:46.140 --> 00:30:46.940 align:middle line:90%
It was his passion.

00:30:46.940 --> 00:30:47.540 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Made him happy.

00:30:47.540 --> 00:30:49.080 align:middle line:90%
>>SHIMOFF: But when he retired--

00:30:49.080 --> 00:30:51.363 align:middle line:84%
he was he was 72
when he retired.

00:30:51.363 --> 00:30:53.780 align:middle line:84%
And what happens statistically
to people when they retire,

00:30:53.780 --> 00:30:54.580 align:middle line:90%
is they die.

00:30:54.580 --> 00:30:55.663 align:middle line:90%
They get sick or they die.

00:30:55.663 --> 00:30:57.290 align:middle line:84%
Not because they're
suddenly older,

00:30:57.290 --> 00:30:59.810 align:middle line:84%
but because they've
lost their passion.

00:30:59.810 --> 00:31:01.880 align:middle line:84%
And my dad said that's
not going to happen to me.

00:31:01.880 --> 00:31:04.890 align:middle line:10%
And he analyzed what he
loved about being a dentist.

00:31:04.890 --> 00:31:06.590 align:middle line:84%
And he realized
that what he loved

00:31:06.590 --> 00:31:09.560 align:middle line:84%
was working with his
hands in intricate ways.

00:31:09.560 --> 00:31:13.670 align:middle line:84%
And he took up his second
profession, needlepoint.

00:31:13.670 --> 00:31:15.410 align:middle line:84%
And he became a
master needlepointer.

00:31:15.410 --> 00:31:17.770 align:middle line:84%
He won awards throughout
all Northern California.

00:31:17.770 --> 00:31:18.770 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Well, how great.

00:31:18.770 --> 00:31:20.395 align:middle line:10%
>>SHIMOFF: He would
go in every morning

00:31:20.395 --> 00:31:23.810 align:middle line:10%
and sit down in my
sister's bedroom

00:31:23.810 --> 00:31:26.450 align:middle line:10%
and put on his dental
magnifying glasses.

00:31:26.450 --> 00:31:28.430 align:middle line:10%
And that was his new
needlepoint office,

00:31:28.430 --> 00:31:30.200 align:middle line:10%
and he would do
his needle points.

00:31:30.200 --> 00:31:33.360 align:middle line:84%
And you know, it's the
idea of doing your passion.

00:31:33.360 --> 00:31:35.600 align:middle line:84%
I mean, Lisa, you are
living your passion.

00:31:35.600 --> 00:31:38.690 align:middle line:90%
And I have never seen a happy--

00:31:38.690 --> 00:31:41.150 align:middle line:84%
really deeply
person-- happy person.

00:31:41.150 --> 00:31:43.820 align:middle line:84%
And I mean, when I say
happy for no reason,

00:31:43.820 --> 00:31:46.280 align:middle line:90%
I mean, happy that lasts.

00:31:46.280 --> 00:31:48.920 align:middle line:84%
I mean an interstate of
peace and well-being that

00:31:48.920 --> 00:31:50.900 align:middle line:90%
isn't dependent on your--

00:31:50.900 --> 00:31:53.240 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Your circumstances,
your conditions, yes.

00:31:53.240 --> 00:31:55.250 align:middle line:84%
>>SHIMOFF: And what I've
seen about happy people

00:31:55.250 --> 00:31:57.860 align:middle line:84%
is that they bring their
happiness to their life

00:31:57.860 --> 00:31:58.940 align:middle line:90%
circumstances.

00:31:58.940 --> 00:32:04.070 align:middle line:84%
They don't wait for life to
bring them their happiness.

00:32:04.070 --> 00:32:05.420 align:middle line:90%
They're happy in the moment.

00:32:05.420 --> 00:32:07.250 align:middle line:84%
Whatever they're
doing, they're happy.

00:32:07.250 --> 00:32:09.717 align:middle line:84%
But they're also, they've
found those things

00:32:09.717 --> 00:32:12.050 align:middle line:84%
that they're on the planet
